/*! \page raw_socket_design Raw Socket Communication Design

\tableofcontents

\section rsd_overview Overview

The raw socket path is used for connections carrying alien protocols -- protocols
that the framework cannot frame itself, such as ASCII FIX, NMEA, or any custom
binary format. In contrast to the PDU path (where the framework identifies complete
message boundaries and only delivers complete PDUs to the application), the raw
socket path delivers bytes as they arrive. The application thread is entirely
responsible for finding message boundaries.

\section rsd_mirrored_buffer MirroredBuffer

The central data structure is the \c MirroredBuffer -- a stream-oriented ring buffer
that uses virtual memory mirroring to provide a contiguous view of unprocessed bytes.

\subsection rsd_why_mirrored Why mirroring?

A conventional ring buffer wraps around: a message that straddles the end of the
buffer appears in two non-contiguous pieces. The application would have to handle
this split-packet case explicitly. The MirroredBuffer eliminates this by mapping the
same physical memory to two adjacent virtual address ranges. Any contiguous slice of
up to \c capacity bytes always appears contiguous in virtual memory, regardless of
where it sits in the ring.

\subsection rsd_implementation Implementation

The buffer is backed by an anonymous shared memory object created with
\c memfd_create. The physical memory is then mapped twice into contiguous virtual
address space using \c mmap with \c MAP_FIXED. The result is that
\c read_ptr()[0..bytes_available()-1] is always a valid contiguous view of all
unprocessed bytes.

\subsection rsd_invariants Threading invariants

- The \b reactor thread is the sole producer: it advances the \b head by calling
  \c advance_head(n) after each successful \c recv().
- The \b reactor thread is also the sole tail advancer: it calls
  \c advance_tail(n) in response to a \c CommitRawBytes command from the
  application thread.
- The \b application thread reads from \c read_ptr() and \c bytes_available()
  but never modifies the buffer directly.
- The head never overtakes the tail (buffer-full policy: disconnect the peer).
- The tail never overtakes the head (precondition enforced by \c advance_tail).

\section rsd_delivery Delivery to the application thread

When \c on_data_ready() fires (EPOLLIN), the reactor:

-# Calls \c recv() into \c write_ptr(), advancing the head.
-# Enqueues a \c RawSocketCommunication \c EventMessage to the application
   thread's Vyukov queue. The message carries:
   - \c connection_id -- so the application can demultiplex multiple connections.
   - \c payload() -- \c read_ptr() at enqueue time (pointer into the MirroredBuffer).
   - \c payload_size() -- \c bytes_available() at enqueue time.
   - \c tail_position() -- the buffer's \c tail_ value at enqueue time.

Crucially, the message delivers \b all currently unprocessed bytes, not just the
newly arrived bytes. If bytes from a previous delivery were not committed, they are
included again in the new delivery.

\section rsd_fragmentation Packet fragmentation

TCP is a stream protocol. A single application-level message may arrive in multiple
TCP segments, and multiple application-level messages may arrive in a single segment.
The application thread must handle both cases.

\subsection rsd_fragmentation_pattern Correct application thread pattern

The application thread subclass tracks two pieces of state:

- \c bytes_decoded_ -- bytes already decoded from the current window (since the
  last tail advance).
- \c last_tail_ -- the \c tail_position() value from the last delivery.

On each \c on_raw_socket_message() call:

-# Compare \c message.tail_position() against \c last_tail_. If different, the
   reactor has processed a previous \c CommitRawBytes and the tail has advanced.
   Reset \c bytes_decoded_ to 0 and update \c last_tail_.
-# Compute \c unprocessed = \c payload_size() - \c bytes_decoded_.
-# Decode from \c payload() + \c bytes_decoded_ for \c unprocessed bytes.
-# If decoding consumed some bytes, update \c bytes_decoded_.
-# \b Only commit when \c bytes_decoded_ == \c payload_size() (the entire current
   window has been consumed). Issue a \c CommitRawBytes command for the delta
   since the last commit.

\subsection rsd_fragmentation_why_cumulative Why only commit when the window is fully consumed?

If a partial message sits at the end of the delivery window and the application
commits only the complete messages, the tail advances past them. The partial bytes
remain in the buffer. But no new \c EPOLLIN fires because no new kernel bytes have
arrived. The partial bytes are stranded -- the application waits forever for a
delivery that never comes.

By not committing until the entire window is consumed, the partial bytes are left
in the buffer. When the next TCP segment arrives, \c EPOLLIN fires, \c on_data_ready
reads the new bytes, and the new delivery includes the partial bytes plus the new
bytes. The application can then decode the previously partial message.

\subsection rsd_fragmentation_rogue_client Rogue client protection

A rogue client that sends a partial message and then goes silent will cause the
application to stop committing. The buffer fills up. When \c space_remaining()
reaches zero, \c on_data_ready() detects the buffer-full condition, logs an error,
and invokes the disconnect handler. The connection is closed. All other connections
and threads in the reactor are unaffected.

\section rsd_tail_position Why tail_position() is needed

The naive approach to detecting tail advances is to compare \c payload_size()
against the previous call's \c payload_size(). If \c payload_size() shrank, the
tail must have advanced.

This is unreliable. Consider:

-# Delivery 1: \c available=15. Application decodes ONE message, commits 15.
   \c last_available_=15.
-# The reactor processes the commit. Tail advances 15. Meanwhile, 30 more bytes
   arrive. Head advances 30. \c bytes_available() = 30.
-# Delivery 2: \c available=30. \c 30 > 15, so the naive check does not detect
   the tail advance. \c bytes_decoded_ is not reset. The application skips the
   first 15 bytes of the new window -- which are now MESSAGE_TWO -- and decodes
   from the wrong offset.

The \c tail_position() field solves this unambiguously. It records the buffer's
\c tail_ value at the moment \c on_data_ready() enqueued the message. The
application compares this against its \c last_tail_. If they differ, the tail
has advanced regardless of what \c payload_size() does.

\section rsd_commit_protocol CommitRawBytes reactor control command

The application thread does not advance the buffer tail directly. It enqueues a
\c CommitRawBytes \c ReactorControlCommand carrying the number of bytes consumed.
The reactor processes this command on its thread and calls
\c RawBytesProtocolHandler::commit_bytes(n), which calls
\c buffer_.advance_tail(n).

This preserves the threading invariant: only the reactor thread ever modifies
the buffer tail.

\section rsd_outbound Outbound path

Outbound raw bytes use the \c SendRaw \c ReactorControlCommand. The application
thread allocates a slab chunk, fills it with the raw bytes to send, and enqueues
a \c SendRaw command. The reactor calls \c send_prebuilt() on the handler, which
delegates to \c PduFramer for partial-send management and slab chunk lifetime.
The outbound path is identical to the PDU path in this respect.

\section rsd_backpressure Backpressure summary

| Condition | Response |
|-----------|----------|
| Buffer full on recv | Disconnect peer; deliver ConnectionLost to app thread |
| Partial message, no new data | Leave in buffer; wait for next EPOLLIN |
| Rogue client fills buffer | Buffer-full disconnect (see above) |
| Slow application thread | Buffer fills; eventually buffer-full disconnect |

*/
